   <h1>Re: [T2] Buying Help '73</h1>
   <b>Andrew Wood &lt;kombi1976_at_yahoo_dot_com&gt;</b><br/>
   <i>2001-10-25 00:16:30+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>You hit the button on those things, Chris.
The best thing to do if you can is take it to a
trustworthy VW specialist & have them put it on a
hoist and do the whole check.
It cost me about $120 here in Australia.
Often the Automobile Association does similar
services.
My own check to add is the windscreen seal & front
skirt.
If it looks dodgy you may be in LOTS of trouble.
Cheers And Happy Hunting
Andrew Wood

--- Chris Mills <scm9985_at_tntech_dot_edu> wrote:
> Look at rust and collision damage. They make small
> magnets to test for rust 
> on car bodies. Check with an Auto Body suppl;y
> store. Not expensive.
> 
> Some rust is acceptable because it is easy to fix
> BUT is it easy for YOU to 
> fix. You don't want seam and frame rust. Harder to
> fix.
> 
> I would be content to know where the rust is so at
> least there are no 
> surprises later.
> 
> Another method is knocking with your knuckles.
> 
> All else can be fixed - some expensive but it can be
> fixed.
> 
> Muir has a good chapter on buying a VW. Get out your
> Muir and Bentley and 
> look at the pics so you know how things should look
> and you know how all 
> the controls work.
> 
> Look for missing stuff (accessories). Headliner
> decent?
> 
> Pull up all the mats and carpets that will come up.
> Anything wet? Rust?
> 
> Will he allow you to wet the car down to look for
> big leaks?
> 
> Check the roof - any CB antenna holes?
> 
> Drive it on the highway and in town.
> 
> Smell the oil for gas.
> 
> See what maintenance is needing to be done. If he
> was sloppy this time, he 
> has been sloppy all the time. Figure this is best
> this bus has looked in a 
> long time, people clean up stuff before they sell
> it.
> 
> Ask why he is selling it.
> 
> Check for a loose front end - on and off the jacks.
> 
> Look under the battery. Rust?
> 
> How many taped together wiring connections? Fire
> hazard?
> 
> Windshield wipers work?
> 
> Lights all work? if not why? Missing wiring,
> corrosion, cut wires? I bought 
> my first car ('66 Mustang) and they were having
> wiring troubles. To isolate 
> the problem the PO cut ALL of the wires to each of
> he exterior and interior 
> lights. They twisted the headlight wires back
> together and taped them. No 
> brake lights, no reverse lights, etc. I did not
> notice 'til much later (Home).
> 
> Does the vehicle sit level? All busses sag a bit in
> the back, but I mean 
> left to right.
> 
> Windows all open and close properly?
> 
> Lock work? Inside and out?
> 
> Any homemade repairs? Incorrect carburetors or
> ignition? Muffler decent? 
> Heater's in fair to good condition?
> 
> Condition of the fuel system? Any fuel leaks?
> 
> Check out the heat. Levers work.
> 
> Feel the bottom panels and the bottom of the doors.
> 
> Check out the radio but test the car without the
> radio so you can hear the 
> car.
> 
> When you first arrive and first look at the engine,
> feel to see if it is 
> warm. Did he pre-start the engine or is it cold? If
> it is warm it may have 
> a dead battery he was trying to charge, hard start
> problem, etc.
> 
> When you leave if you bought it - ask for all the
> papers and books and 
> spares he has. He might forget some.
> 
> 
> At 12:56 PM 10/24/01 -0700, you wrote:
> >Hi All,
> >
> >I may be buying a 73' westy hard top this weekend. 
> I will probably have
> >about 30 minutes to decide if I want it or not
> since it is located about 2
> >hours away.  He has been very open with the
> condition of the engine and
> >exterior/interior and says it runs great, no issues
> at all.  He has done
> >lots of work with the engine.
> >
> >So,  any tips or tricks on what to look for when I
> check it out?
> >
> >Also, what should I expect to pay for something
> like this.  The paint is
> >good, only rust is on the bumpers, 2-3 minor dents,
> great working engine,
> >and the mattress is in good shape.
> >Just a ballpark figure....
> >
> >
></pre>


